1
00:01:17,502 --> 00:01:19,212
Ellie?

2
00:01:19,338 --> 00:01:21,548
Ellie, hurry up!
We've only got five minutes.

3
00:01:21,673 --> 00:01:23,008
I'll be right down.

4
00:01:43,111 --> 00:01:44,946
I'd like to say a few words
about what's happened

5
00:01:45,072 --> 00:01:47,032
to me over the past year.

6
00:01:47,157 --> 00:01:49,576
You women may not sympathize.
You think men have it easy.

7
00:01:49,701 --> 00:01:51,870
But that's where you're wrong.

8
00:01:51,995 --> 00:01:54,998
Man is a very delicate
and sensitive mechanism.

9
00:01:55,123 --> 00:01:56,958
If you treat him right,
you flatter him

10
00:01:57,084 --> 00:02:00,087
and butter him up a little bit,
he's good for years.

11
00:02:00,212 --> 00:02:02,047
But if somebody
rocks the boat...

12
00:02:03,256 --> 00:02:06,927
Well, you know how it is, men.

13
00:02:07,886 --> 00:02:10,013
You work hard for years,
trying to build a home,

14
00:02:10,138 --> 00:02:14,101
raise a family, and then
comes one wonderful day

15
00:02:14,226 --> 00:02:15,602
when, for the first time
in your life,

16
00:02:15,727 --> 00:02:16,978
you feel you're a little
ahead of the game.

17
00:02:17,104 --> 00:02:18,647
Things have eased up
at the office.

18
00:02:18,772 --> 00:02:23,360
The kids are all set, married
or well along in school or both,

19
00:02:23,485 --> 00:02:25,696
and you're raring to go.

20
00:02:25,821 --> 00:02:27,531
You think of all
the wonderful things

21
00:02:27,656 --> 00:02:30,325
you would have done in your life
if you just had time.

22
00:02:32,452 --> 00:02:33,704
You go fishing.

23
00:02:34,496 --> 00:02:35,789
You go big-game hunting.

24
00:02:35,914 --> 00:02:38,500
You might even climb
Mount Everest.

25
00:02:38,625 --> 00:02:41,002
Anyway, you're on
top of the world.

26
00:02:41,128 --> 00:02:42,629
You begin to feel
you're a combination

27
00:02:42,754 --> 00:02:44,589
of Don Juan and Columbus.

28
00:02:46,633 --> 00:02:49,761
And that's just the moment
they choose to let you have it.

29
00:02:52,973 --> 00:02:55,308
I remember it was
just a year ago today.

30
00:02:57,018 --> 00:02:59,730
I caught my usual
commuter's train.

31
00:02:59,855 --> 00:03:01,314
It was late, as usual.

32
00:03:01,440 --> 00:03:03,734
It was such a beautiful day
that I let the bus go by

33
00:03:03,859 --> 00:03:06,236
and walked home
from the station.

34
00:03:06,361 --> 00:03:08,822
It was one of those
first warm days in May

35
00:03:08,947 --> 00:03:11,158
when everything seems
to come to life.

36
00:03:11,283 --> 00:03:14,119
I felt particularly well.

37
00:03:14,244 --> 00:03:15,871
I was thinking
what a lucky man I was,

38
00:03:15,996 --> 00:03:17,497
with a nice house all paid for,

39
00:03:17,622 --> 00:03:21,168
three children all paid for,
and a beautiful wife.

40
00:03:24,713 --> 00:03:26,339
Ellie.

41
00:03:26,465 --> 00:03:28,175
- Oh, hi, Pa.
- Hi, boys. Hello, Del.

42
00:03:28,300 --> 00:03:30,177
- Mr. Banks.
- Ellie, I'm home!

43
00:03:31,136 --> 00:03:32,345
Coming.

44
00:03:33,805 --> 00:03:35,098
Ellie was radiant that night.

45
00:03:35,223 --> 00:03:37,017
She seemed to be
floating on air.

46
00:03:37,726 --> 00:03:39,352
Stanley, what kept you?
It's late.

47
00:03:39,478 --> 00:03:41,062
Such a nice day, I walked.

48
00:03:48,570 --> 00:03:50,030
Stanley!

49
00:03:50,155 --> 00:03:52,157
What's the matter?
Can't a fella kiss his wife?

50
00:03:55,160 --> 00:03:56,703
Oh, you won't have time
to change.

51
00:03:56,828 --> 00:03:57,954
We have to start right away.

52
00:03:58,079 --> 00:03:59,039
Why? Where are we going?

53
00:03:59,164 --> 00:04:00,707
Kay and Buckley asked us
to their apartment

54
00:04:00,832 --> 00:04:01,708
for dinner tonight.

55
00:04:01,833 --> 00:04:04,002
She phoned this morning,
said she had some good news.

56
00:04:04,127 --> 00:04:06,004
Oh! Oh! Buckley put over
the deal, I guess,

57
00:04:06,129 --> 00:04:07,130
with the chain stores, huh?

58
00:04:07,255 --> 00:04:08,673
That plastic bag of his?

59
00:04:08,799 --> 00:04:10,217
Oh, I don't think
that's their big news.

60
00:04:10,342 --> 00:04:12,219
I think it's something
much more important that that.

61
00:04:12,344 --> 00:04:14,554
More important than that? Why?
That means thousands of dollars.

62
00:04:14,679 --> 00:04:16,807
I don't know. What could be
more important than that?

63
00:04:16,932 --> 00:04:18,517
Something, nothing.

64
00:04:18,642 --> 00:04:19,851
- Get my coat, will you, dear?
- Yeah.

65
00:04:19,976 --> 00:04:21,102
Night, Tommy.
Night, Ben.

66
00:04:21,228 --> 00:04:22,395
Good night, Mom.

67
00:04:22,521 --> 00:04:24,231
Kay said she was sorry
she couldn't have you, too,

68
00:04:24,356 --> 00:04:27,108
but she had to have Buckley's
father and mother.

69
00:04:27,234 --> 00:04:28,568
- Is Kay gonna cook?
- Mm-hmm.

70
00:04:28,693 --> 00:04:30,111
You better take
your bicarb with you.

71
00:04:30,237 --> 00:04:31,738
Oh, no.

72
00:04:31,863 --> 00:04:33,698
- Oh, boys, don't keep Delilah.
- Son, son, your jokes

73
00:04:33,824 --> 00:04:35,534
- get funnier every year.
- Stanley, please!

74
00:04:35,659 --> 00:04:36,993
I promised her
she could go to the movie.

75
00:04:37,118 --> 00:04:38,787
Ben, you drop her on your way
to the game.

76
00:04:38,912 --> 00:04:41,623
Oh, and, uh, Delilah,
stack the dishes until after.

77
00:04:41,748 --> 00:04:42,833
You'll miss the first
of the picture.

78
00:04:42,958 --> 00:04:44,918
- Thanks, Miss Banks.
- Um, Tommy don't study too late.

79
00:04:45,043 --> 00:04:47,128
Remember, if the rug man calls,
tell him to call â€”

80
00:04:47,254 --> 00:04:48,880
S-Stanley!

81
00:04:50,173 --> 00:04:51,383
What's got into you?

82
00:04:51,508 --> 00:04:52,801
It's spring.

83
00:04:54,427 --> 00:04:55,428
It must be.

84
00:04:58,348 --> 00:04:59,975
Yes, sir, we're in a rut, Ellie.

85
00:05:00,100 --> 00:05:01,351
Not that it isn't
a pleasant rut,

86
00:05:01,476 --> 00:05:02,686
but I think we ought to
get out of it.

87
00:05:02,811 --> 00:05:04,396
You know, you're
a very beautiful woman, Ellie.

88
00:05:04,521 --> 00:05:05,438
Why, Stan.

89
00:05:05,564 --> 00:05:07,691
A very, very beautiful woman.

90
00:05:07,816 --> 00:05:09,109
Trouble is, I never see you.

91
00:05:09,234 --> 00:05:10,402
Come home at night,
you wanna know

92
00:05:10,527 --> 00:05:11,528
if I've seen the hole
in the carpet

93
00:05:11,653 --> 00:05:13,029
or whether I'll fix
the leaky faucet.

94
00:05:13,154 --> 00:05:14,072
I'm sorry.

95
00:05:14,197 --> 00:05:16,157
Oh, I don't mean that
it's your fault. No.

96
00:05:16,283 --> 00:05:17,659
I think we ought
to forgot about it, though.

97
00:05:17,784 --> 00:05:19,536
We ought to forget the house,
forget the whole thing,

98
00:05:19,661 --> 00:05:21,037
go away and take a trip.

99
00:05:21,162 --> 00:05:24,249
No reason why we can't.
We're as free as the air.

100
00:05:24,374 --> 00:05:26,418
Kinda like when we were
first married.

101
00:05:27,252 --> 00:05:28,837
Before Kay came along.

102
00:05:28,962 --> 00:05:30,755
Only this time we're not broke.

103
00:05:30,881 --> 00:05:32,007
We could even go to Europe.

104
00:05:32,132 --> 00:05:34,426
I think we better wait
and hear what Kay has to say.

105
00:05:34,551 --> 00:05:36,887
Honolulu! What about Honolulu?
That's the place.

106
00:05:37,012 --> 00:05:38,513
- How about it, Ellie?
- We'll see.

107
00:05:38,638 --> 00:05:39,931
Oh, sure.

108
00:05:40,056 --> 00:05:44,019
Waikiki beach,
moonlight on Waikiki.

109
00:05:44,144 --> 00:05:46,688
Flowers, ukulele, romance.

110
00:05:52,444 --> 00:05:54,487
Well, I'm gonna call up that
travel agency in the morning,

111
00:05:54,613 --> 00:05:56,239
find out about those trailers.

112
00:05:57,949 --> 00:06:00,118
- Hi, there!
- Hello, darling!

113
00:06:00,243 --> 00:06:03,705
There she was, my Kay,
the darling of my heart.

114
00:06:03,830 --> 00:06:06,333
I couldn't yet believe
she was a married woman.

115
00:06:06,458 --> 00:06:09,961
She still seemed like kid to me
playing at keeping house.

116
00:06:10,086 --> 00:06:11,671
How are you?
You feeling alright?

117
00:06:11,796 --> 00:06:14,007
Feeling alright?
Look at her. How does she look?

118
00:06:14,132 --> 00:06:15,133
Never looked better in her life.

119
00:06:15,258 --> 00:06:17,010
Oh, thank you, Pops.

120
00:06:17,844 --> 00:06:20,013
- How's he treating you?
- Oh, fine.

121
00:06:20,138 --> 00:06:22,807
- You miss me?
- Hmm, don't talk.

122
00:06:22,933 --> 00:06:24,392
- Hello, hello!
- Buckley dear.

123
00:06:24,517 --> 00:06:27,020
I was full of the milk
of human kindness that night.

124
00:06:27,145 --> 00:06:30,023
I even looked at my son-in-law
with a friendly eye.

125
00:06:30,148 --> 00:06:31,983
I don't say
that he was my ideal,

126
00:06:32,108 --> 00:06:33,526
but I was getting used to him.

127
00:06:33,652 --> 00:06:35,779
Father Banks, how are you?
Nice to see you!

128
00:06:35,904 --> 00:06:38,365
How have you been?
Oh, give me your hat!

129
00:06:38,490 --> 00:06:40,742
Say, uh, do you think
we could kinda do away

130
00:06:40,867 --> 00:06:42,077
with that "Father Banks" stuff?

131
00:06:42,202 --> 00:06:44,537
- Just call me Stanley.
- Okay, Stan.

132
00:06:44,663 --> 00:06:46,665
Alright, not Stan.
Stanley.

133
00:06:46,790 --> 00:06:47,916
- Stanley?
- Yeah.

134
00:06:48,041 --> 00:06:49,209
Okay, Stanley.

135
00:06:49,334 --> 00:06:50,460
How about little golf
on Sunday?

136
00:06:50,585 --> 00:06:51,586
Ah, you're on.

137
00:06:51,711 --> 00:06:54,547
Doris, it's wonderful
to see you again.

138
00:06:54,673 --> 00:06:56,424
Well, Herbert boy, how are you?

139
00:06:56,549 --> 00:06:57,509
Oh, so-so.

140
00:06:57,634 --> 00:06:59,302
So-so?
Why, you look wonderful.

141
00:06:59,427 --> 00:07:01,012
- Doris, how are you?
- How are you?

142
00:07:01,137 --> 00:07:02,180
What's wrong with the old man?

143
00:07:02,305 --> 00:07:04,224
It's the spring.
It always takes it out of him.

144
00:07:04,349 --> 00:07:06,434
Takes it out? Puts it into me,
doesn't it, Ellie?

145
00:07:06,559 --> 00:07:08,436
I suppose you got
the same message we did.

146
00:07:08,561 --> 00:07:09,562
- Very important news.
- Yes, yes.

147
00:07:09,688 --> 00:07:10,689
That's right.

148
00:07:10,814 --> 00:07:12,857
- Kay, I can't wait.
- You have your cocktail.

149
00:07:12,983 --> 00:07:14,901
Oh, darling,
you can't do this to us.

150
00:07:15,026 --> 00:07:16,820
Buckley, you tell us.
We're all here now.

151
00:07:16,945 --> 00:07:18,613
- Thank you, Buckley.
- Hope it's what I hope it is.

152
00:07:18,738 --> 00:07:20,907
I know what it is.
Great news, eh, Buckley?

153
00:07:21,032 --> 00:07:22,575
Well, I-I think it is.

154
00:07:22,701 --> 00:07:25,537
Oh, Buckley did you tell them
and not tell us?

155
00:07:25,662 --> 00:07:27,664
No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no.
I guessed it.

156
00:07:27,789 --> 00:07:28,873
You really put it over,
didn't you, boy?

157
00:07:28,999 --> 00:07:31,001
Oh, Buckley, he's not right.
It's not that horrid contract.

158
00:07:31,126 --> 00:07:32,460
A contract?
Is that what it is?

159
00:07:32,585 --> 00:07:34,129
Thousands of dollars.

160
00:07:34,254 --> 00:07:36,339
Oh, and we hoped it was a baby.

161
00:07:36,464 --> 00:07:39,384
Oh, I prayed for a baby,
and now to hear this.

162
00:07:39,509 --> 00:07:41,428
But, Mom, that's what it is.
It is a baby!

163
00:07:41,553 --> 00:07:43,179
- A baby!
- What? A baby?

164
00:07:43,304 --> 00:07:45,807
Oh, Buckley, that's wonderful!

165
00:07:45,932 --> 00:07:47,976
Oh-ho, congratulations!

166
00:07:48,101 --> 00:07:50,186
I'd never seen such excitement.

167
00:07:50,311 --> 00:07:52,105
Kay was passed around
like a loving cup.

168
00:07:52,230 --> 00:07:53,773
I can't tell you
how delighted I am.

169
00:07:55,734 --> 00:07:58,028
Buckley stood by
trying to look modest.

170
00:07:58,153 --> 00:08:00,780
He only succeeded in looking
slightly half-witted.

171
00:08:04,617 --> 00:08:06,286
I grinned and tried to join in,

172
00:08:06,411 --> 00:08:09,080
but somehow there was
a fly in the ointment.

173
00:08:09,205 --> 00:08:12,917
I couldn't put my finger on it,
but there was definitely a fly.

174
00:08:13,043 --> 00:08:16,254
Yes, sir. That's the greatest
news I've had in years.

175
00:08:16,379 --> 00:08:18,006
How about that, Grandpa?

176
00:08:21,384 --> 00:08:22,594
Grandpa!

177
00:08:22,719 --> 00:08:24,304
That was the fly.

178
00:08:25,930 --> 00:08:27,348
Grandpa.

179
00:08:28,433 --> 00:08:30,018
First he steals my daughter.

180
00:08:30,143 --> 00:08:32,020
Now he makes
a grandpa out of me.

181
00:08:34,606 --> 00:08:36,191
I do wish she'd go to Dr. Barns.

182
00:08:36,316 --> 00:08:38,693
After all, he's taken care
of her all her life.

183
00:08:38,818 --> 00:08:41,196
But I suppose this man
is alright, though.

184
00:08:41,321 --> 00:08:43,823
Good gracious, November.
That doesn't give me much time.

185
00:08:43,948 --> 00:08:45,825
And I have a million
things to do.

186
00:08:45,950 --> 00:08:47,243
Ben? Tommy?

187
00:08:47,368 --> 00:08:48,995
- What do you want them for?
- I want to tell 'em.

188
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:50,955
Ben? Tommy? Wake up.

189
00:08:51,081 --> 00:08:54,334
Tommy, Ben.
Boys, do you hear me?

190
00:08:54,459 --> 00:08:56,419
Something wrong?
What is it?

191
00:08:56,544 --> 00:08:59,172
- What's the matter?
- The most exciting news.

192
00:08:59,297 --> 00:09:00,840
Kay is having a baby.

193
00:09:01,966 --> 00:09:03,134
Right now?

194
00:09:03,259 --> 00:09:05,178
- No, silly, November.
- Poor Buckley.

195
00:09:05,303 --> 00:09:06,596
"Poor Buckley?"
What do you mean, poor Buckley?

196
00:09:06,721 --> 00:09:07,931
You wouldn't say that
if you'd been there tonight.

197
00:09:08,056 --> 00:09:09,182
He was just bursting with pride.

198
00:09:09,307 --> 00:09:10,892
We were standing there telling
him how delighted we were,

199
00:09:11,017 --> 00:09:13,311
and he just stood there
looking sort of cute and shy.

200
00:09:13,436 --> 00:09:15,063
Wasn't he cute, Stanley?

201
00:09:15,188 --> 00:09:16,481
Cutest thing you ever saw.

202
00:09:16,606 --> 00:09:18,316
Oh, alright, alright.
You're all alike, you men.

203
00:09:18,441 --> 00:09:19,692
Good night, Tommy.
Sorry I woke you up.

204
00:09:19,818 --> 00:09:21,569
Now night, Ben.
Go back to your book.

205
00:09:21,694 --> 00:09:24,239
Good night, Ben.
Good night, Tommy.

206
00:09:24,364 --> 00:09:28,701
Um, no need of broadcasting
this, you know.

207
00:09:36,126 --> 00:09:37,544
Mrs. Dickson, please.

208
00:09:37,669 --> 00:09:39,420
Ellie, what are you doing
calling people up

209
00:09:39,546 --> 00:09:40,463
at this time of the night?

210
00:09:40,588 --> 00:09:41,881
Will you please ask her
to call Mrs. Banks

211
00:09:42,006 --> 00:09:42,882
the minute she comes in?

212
00:09:43,007 --> 00:09:45,135
I have some very important
news to tell her.

213
00:09:45,260 --> 00:09:46,678
Mrs. Dickson
would not forgive me

214
00:09:46,803 --> 00:09:48,096
if I didn't tell her right away.

215
00:09:48,221 --> 00:09:49,681
You know, I think
I'll give Kay a baby shower.

216
00:09:49,806 --> 00:09:50,765
We could have it on a Saturday

217
00:09:50,890 --> 00:09:52,016
and you could ask the men
to come in afterwards.

218
00:09:52,142 --> 00:09:53,768
Ellie, do we really have to
blaze this thing

219
00:09:53,893 --> 00:09:55,395
- from the housetops?
- Huh?

220
00:09:55,520 --> 00:09:57,856
You know, after all,
it really isn't our affair.

221
00:09:57,981 --> 00:09:59,274
Stanley, what's
the matter with you?

222
00:09:59,399 --> 00:10:01,276
I swear you act as though
you almost didn't like the idea.

223
00:10:01,401 --> 00:10:02,610
I don't!

224
00:10:02,735 --> 00:10:04,779
Why, Stanley?
For heaven's sake, why?

225
00:10:04,904 --> 00:10:06,865
I'll tell you why, exactly why.

226
00:10:06,990 --> 00:10:08,741
In the first place, they haven't
got room enough for a baby.

227
00:10:08,867 --> 00:10:09,909
The little apartment
they live in

228
00:10:10,034 --> 00:10:12,162
isn't big enough for the two
of them, much less a baby.

229
00:10:12,287 --> 00:10:13,788
Second place,
they can't afford a baby.

230
00:10:13,913 --> 00:10:15,039
Babies cost money.

231
00:10:15,165 --> 00:10:16,875
The older they get,
the more they cost.

232
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:18,334
What do they think
they're gonna use for money?

233
00:10:18,459 --> 00:10:19,419
You heard him tonight,
didn't you?

234
00:10:19,544 --> 00:10:21,004
When I asked him if he had
the contract, said no,

235
00:10:21,129 --> 00:10:22,255
but did that faze him?

236
00:10:22,380 --> 00:10:23,506
Oh, no, no.

237
00:10:23,631 --> 00:10:25,383
He just stood there
looking cute.

238
00:10:25,508 --> 00:10:28,595
Cute? And he's the one
who's going to be the father.

239
00:10:28,720 --> 00:10:29,762
Well, I'll tell you something.

240
00:10:29,888 --> 00:10:31,681
If he's got any idea
that I'm gonna pay for it,

241
00:10:31,806 --> 00:10:32,765
he's got another thing coming.

242
00:10:32,891 --> 00:10:34,767
I just got through
paying for the wedding.

243
00:10:34,893 --> 00:10:36,686
And another thing â€”
I think they ought to wait.

244
00:10:36,811 --> 00:10:37,937
Wait? For what?

245
00:10:38,062 --> 00:10:39,689
For seven or eight years,
that's what.

246
00:10:39,814 --> 00:10:40,773
What do they know
about children?

247
00:10:40,899 --> 00:10:42,066
My Kay is just a child herself.

248
00:10:42,192 --> 00:10:43,151
Here she gets out of college,

249
00:10:43,276 --> 00:10:45,153
marries the first guy
she comes in contact with.

250
00:10:45,278 --> 00:10:46,529
Now she's saddled with a baby.

251
00:10:46,654 --> 00:10:48,823
Stanley Banks, you listen to me.

252
00:10:48,948 --> 00:10:51,034
I left school to marry you.
Do you remember that?

253
00:10:51,159 --> 00:10:52,619
And do you remember
when we were married?

254
00:10:52,744 --> 00:10:53,953
Of course you don't.

255
00:10:54,078 --> 00:10:55,622
We were married
on the 4th of September.

256
00:10:55,747 --> 00:10:56,915
What's that
got to do with it?

257
00:10:57,040 --> 00:10:58,708
And do you remember
when Kay was born?

258
00:10:58,833 --> 00:11:00,251
The 21st of June.

259
00:11:00,376 --> 00:11:01,711
Exactly.

260
00:11:01,836 --> 00:11:04,339
While my class was up there
on the platform graduating,

261
00:11:04,464 --> 00:11:05,757
I was home having a baby.

262
00:11:05,882 --> 00:11:07,425
Well, I don't...

263
00:11:08,259 --> 00:11:11,679
Oh, Stanley, I-I-I know
they haven't money

264
00:11:11,804 --> 00:11:14,182
and the apartment is small,

265
00:11:14,307 --> 00:11:17,560
but those things don't
really matter, do they?

266
00:11:17,685 --> 00:11:19,145
The important thing is that

267
00:11:19,270 --> 00:11:21,105
we're going to have
a grandchild.

268
00:11:22,148 --> 00:11:25,610
Darling, it's like
getting a dividend.

269
00:11:25,735 --> 00:11:27,362
It's like getting a dividend?

270
00:11:27,487 --> 00:11:30,865
Yeah, something comes to you and
you don't even lift a finger.

271
00:11:30,990 --> 00:11:33,576
You have none of the
responsibilities of a baby,

272
00:11:33,701 --> 00:11:35,203
none of the hardships.

273
00:11:35,328 --> 00:11:37,538
All you have to do is love it.

274
00:11:40,875 --> 00:11:44,671
Hello? Ruth? I have the most
marvelous news for you.

275
00:11:44,796 --> 00:11:46,756
I am going to be a grandmother.

276
00:11:46,881 --> 00:11:49,384
- "It's like getting a dividend."
- Yes! Isn't that divine?

277
00:11:49,509 --> 00:11:50,677
Oh, we're so excited!

278
00:11:50,802 --> 00:11:52,845
Yes, Kay told us about it
tonight.

279
00:11:55,223 --> 00:11:57,308
Ellie didn't seem
to mind the idea.

280
00:11:57,433 --> 00:12:01,145
Maybe women were different, but
when I thought a grandfather...

281
00:12:01,938 --> 00:12:04,148
Why, I was the guy
who was going places.

282
00:12:04,274 --> 00:12:05,984
The whole world of adventure
was waiting,

283
00:12:06,109 --> 00:12:08,361
just waiting for me
to give it the nod.

284
00:12:08,486 --> 00:12:10,488
And now a grandfather.

285
00:12:10,613 --> 00:12:13,449
I thought of the other
grandfathers I knew.

286
00:12:13,574 --> 00:12:15,743
Why, they were old, old men.

287
00:12:15,868 --> 00:12:18,871
The toothless old codger
down the street.

288
00:12:18,997 --> 00:12:20,581
That client of ours
whose only fun

289
00:12:20,707 --> 00:12:22,166
was cutting people
out of his will.

290
00:12:24,085 --> 00:12:26,004
Those ancient dodos
at the club.

291
00:12:26,129 --> 00:12:27,547
You'd have to use a stethoscope

292
00:12:27,672 --> 00:12:29,048
to be sure
they were still living.

293
00:12:31,259 --> 00:12:32,510
I didn't belong with them.

294
00:12:32,635 --> 00:12:34,262
I wasn't ready
for the mothballs yet.

295
00:12:34,387 --> 00:12:36,597
Why, I hadn't even
begun to live.

296
00:12:38,349 --> 00:12:41,686
Only trouble with me was, I
was a little out of condition.

297
00:12:41,811 --> 00:12:43,604
I spent the next afternoon
in the gym.

298
00:13:11,758 --> 00:13:13,926
Oh, that's fine.
Fine, thank you.

299
00:13:15,845 --> 00:13:17,805
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

300
00:13:19,015 --> 00:13:21,267
That evening
I felt like a million.

301
00:13:22,935 --> 00:13:25,229
But the next morning,
I felt closer to 100.

302
00:13:33,154 --> 00:13:34,197
Oh!

303
00:13:35,323 --> 00:13:36,324
Oh.

304
00:13:37,700 --> 00:13:39,577
Stanley, Buckley's here
for your golf match.

305
00:13:39,702 --> 00:13:41,245
- Oh!
- What's the matter?

306
00:13:41,371 --> 00:13:42,372
What have you done?

307
00:13:42,497 --> 00:13:43,581
Oh, oh, oh, nothing.

308
00:13:43,706 --> 00:13:45,124
Here, here, here,
let me help you.

309
00:13:45,249 --> 00:13:47,168
- Oh, no, no.
- Where's the pain?

310
00:13:47,293 --> 00:13:48,169
It's â€” It's all over.

311
00:13:48,294 --> 00:13:49,962
Oh, whatever did you do?
What happened?

312
00:13:50,088 --> 00:13:51,756
I'll call Dr. Barns and get him
over here right away.

313
00:13:51,881 --> 00:13:53,383
No, I don't want any doctor.

314
00:13:53,508 --> 00:13:55,259
Stanley, for all we know,
it might be your appendix.

315
00:13:55,385 --> 00:13:56,594
If â€” How could â€”

316
00:13:56,719 --> 00:13:58,721
I haven't got an appendix,
and you know it.

317
00:13:58,846 --> 00:14:00,848
- Well, I'll get Buckley.
- Buckley?

318
00:14:00,973 --> 00:14:03,601
If I don't want a doctor,
I certainly don't want Buckley.

319
00:14:03,726 --> 00:14:06,020
Well, I thought
he might be able to help.

320
00:14:06,145 --> 00:14:08,314
Help? Don't you think
he's done enough?

321
00:14:08,439 --> 00:14:11,150
All I want is a hot bath
with some Epsom salts.

322
00:14:11,275 --> 00:14:12,985
Alright, I'll tell Buckley
and be right back.

323
00:14:13,111 --> 00:14:14,237
Oh, Buckley!

324
00:14:14,362 --> 00:14:16,447
Buckley. Oh, oh, oh.

325
00:14:20,493 --> 00:14:24,038
The next week Ellie gave what
she called a "stork shower."

326
00:14:24,163 --> 00:14:26,124
This is one form
of highway robbery

327
00:14:26,249 --> 00:14:27,667
not punishable by law.

328
00:14:33,256 --> 00:14:36,467
Kay! Kay, here's one here
you haven't opened.

329
00:14:36,592 --> 00:14:38,469
Delilah, be sure
to keep all the cards.

330
00:14:38,594 --> 00:14:39,637
Yes, Miss Banks.

331
00:14:39,762 --> 00:14:41,180
Stanley?

332
00:14:42,473 --> 00:14:44,308
Stanley, how wonderful
that you got home in time.

333
00:14:44,434 --> 00:14:46,144
You should see
the things they gave Kay.

334
00:14:46,269 --> 00:14:49,230
Everyone was so sweet.
They all brought her something.

335
00:14:49,355 --> 00:14:50,773
What else could they do, honey?

336
00:14:50,898 --> 00:14:52,817
Oh, Stanley,
you make it sound so sordid.

337
00:14:52,942 --> 00:14:54,402
- Go on in. Kay's in there.
- Oh, no, no, no, no.

338
00:14:54,527 --> 00:14:55,695
That's no place for a man.

339
00:14:55,820 --> 00:14:58,614
Hi, Pops!
Where you going?

340
00:14:58,739 --> 00:15:00,366
Don't you wanna come in
and see my plunder?

341
00:15:00,491 --> 00:15:01,826
- Well, I-I'll see it later.
- Oh, come on.

342
00:15:01,951 --> 00:15:03,828
Stanley, when you're finished,
I have something very important

343
00:15:03,953 --> 00:15:04,954
I wanna talk over with you.

344
00:15:05,079 --> 00:15:06,080
- I'll be in the kitchen.
- Alright.

345
00:15:06,205 --> 00:15:07,081
You just got to see.

346
00:15:07,206 --> 00:15:08,749
The cutest things
I've ever seen.

347
00:15:18,468 --> 00:15:21,512
Well, fine.
Now, I have to go now.

348
00:15:21,637 --> 00:15:23,097
Oh, no, no, go over
and talk to Buckley.

349
00:15:23,222 --> 00:15:24,557
He's just all by himself
over there.

350
00:15:27,310 --> 00:15:28,769
Buckley looked like
a man going down

351
00:15:28,895 --> 00:15:31,397
for the third and last time.

352
00:15:31,522 --> 00:15:33,858
But I decided to let him
stew in his own juice.

353
00:15:33,983 --> 00:15:35,234
I have to talk to Ellie.

354
00:15:40,823 --> 00:15:42,158
Well, what do you want, Ma?

355
00:15:43,326 --> 00:15:44,494
Alright.

356
00:15:45,870 --> 00:15:49,790
I, uh, wanted to talk to you
before the Dunstans got here.

357
00:15:49,916 --> 00:15:51,250
You know how worried I've been

358
00:15:51,375 --> 00:15:53,419
about how we're gonna
rattle around in this house

359
00:15:53,544 --> 00:15:56,214
after Ben leaves
for school in the fall.

360
00:15:56,339 --> 00:15:57,215
Mm-hmm.

361
00:15:57,340 --> 00:15:59,175
Well, I had
a wonderful idea today.

362
00:15:59,300 --> 00:16:00,885
Uh-huh.

363
00:16:01,010 --> 00:16:04,972
I say we ask Kay and Buckley
to move in with us.

364
00:16:05,097 --> 00:16:06,516
Ellie, are you crazy?

365
00:16:07,141 --> 00:16:09,644
Stanley, it'd be so simple.

366
00:16:09,769 --> 00:16:13,064
We could make a sitting room for
them out of Kay's old bedroom

367
00:16:13,189 --> 00:16:15,691
and knock through a door
to Ben's room,

368
00:16:15,816 --> 00:16:17,527
and that could be their bedroom.

369
00:16:17,652 --> 00:16:20,279
Then if we put Tommy
in the spare room,

370
00:16:20,404 --> 00:16:22,865
we could put connecting doors
from the bathroom,

371
00:16:22,990 --> 00:16:26,202
and that would be the nursery
right next to our room.

372
00:16:26,327 --> 00:16:27,870
We could even knock through
a door to our room

373
00:16:27,995 --> 00:16:28,955
so if the baby crâ€”

374
00:16:29,080 --> 00:16:30,957
Yes, that will be
getting nowhere, Ellie.

375
00:16:31,082 --> 00:16:31,832
No.

376
00:16:31,958 --> 00:16:33,751
Stanley, it won't cost much.

377
00:16:33,876 --> 00:16:35,920
I had the contractor
over here today.

378
00:16:36,045 --> 00:16:37,797
It's a perfect place
for the baby,

379
00:16:37,922 --> 00:16:39,632
and the wonderful thing
would be that

380
00:16:39,757 --> 00:16:41,300
if they wanted to go out
some evening

381
00:16:41,425 --> 00:16:42,843
or even go away
for a week or two,

382
00:16:42,969 --> 00:16:43,886
they wouldn't have to worry.

383
00:16:44,011 --> 00:16:45,721
We'd be right here
to take care of it.

384
00:16:45,846 --> 00:16:46,764
Now, look, Ellie.

385
00:16:46,889 --> 00:16:48,641
I know how anxious you've been

386
00:16:48,766 --> 00:16:50,560
to get your hooks
into that baby.

387
00:16:50,685 --> 00:16:51,811
But the answer is no.

388
00:16:51,936 --> 00:16:53,104
I've been all
through that, you know.

389
00:16:53,229 --> 00:16:55,606
The 2:00 feedings
and the colic and the measles

390
00:16:55,731 --> 00:16:57,817
and all the rest of it, and I'm
not going through it again,

391
00:16:57,942 --> 00:16:59,777
especially with
somebody else's baby.

392
00:16:59,902 --> 00:17:01,529
But it wouldn't be
like that, Stanley.

393
00:17:01,654 --> 00:17:03,030
It would be fun
to have a baby here.

394
00:17:03,155 --> 00:17:05,116
Yeah, you can go over and see
the baby at their apartment

395
00:17:05,241 --> 00:17:06,784
when they get it all
washed and ironed,

396
00:17:06,909 --> 00:17:08,869
but it's not coming here,
and that's final.

397
00:17:08,995 --> 00:17:10,454
Well, you know that apartment
isn't big enough.

398
00:17:10,580 --> 00:17:11,831
Alright, tell them
to buy a house.

399
00:17:11,956 --> 00:17:13,207
They can't afford a house.

400
00:17:13,332 --> 00:17:15,001
They should have thought
of that before.

401
00:17:16,335 --> 00:17:18,504
I don't understand
how you can be so hard

402
00:17:18,629 --> 00:17:21,257
on a poor innocent little baby.

403
00:17:22,842 --> 00:17:24,677
Mom, Pops,
the Dunstans are here.

404
00:17:24,802 --> 00:17:25,928
Would you please come out
and talk to them?

405
00:17:26,053 --> 00:17:27,597
I gotta say goodbye
to the girls.

406
00:17:27,722 --> 00:17:29,056
Of course.

407
00:17:31,517 --> 00:17:32,560
Come on, Stanley.

408
00:17:37,898 --> 00:17:40,568
Doris, Herbert, we were afraid
you weren't coming.

409
00:17:40,693 --> 00:17:42,570
Well, well, Ellie.

410
00:17:42,695 --> 00:17:43,904
Hello, Doris.

411
00:17:44,739 --> 00:17:46,490
And how's Grandpa Banks?

412
00:17:46,616 --> 00:17:47,825
Why? What's the matter?

413
00:17:47,950 --> 00:17:49,827
Well, I'm a little stiff.
I've been taking some exercise.

414
00:17:49,952 --> 00:17:51,495
Exercise?
Well, you're crazy.

415
00:17:51,621 --> 00:17:52,830
Look at me, fit as fiddle.

416
00:17:52,955 --> 00:17:54,582
I always say
the only exercise I get

417
00:17:54,707 --> 00:17:56,417
is burying the men that take it.

418
00:17:57,627 --> 00:17:59,086
Really, this baby's
the best thing

419
00:17:59,211 --> 00:18:00,463
that ever happened to Herbert.

420
00:18:00,588 --> 00:18:02,173
It's given him
a new lease on life.

421
00:18:02,298 --> 00:18:04,800
- Sit down. I'll have Delilah â€”
- Oh, no, no, no, not now.

422
00:18:04,925 --> 00:18:07,803
You sit down, Ellie.
You sit down.

423
00:18:07,928 --> 00:18:09,263
Ooh, I beg your pardon, dear,

424
00:18:09,388 --> 00:18:11,515
because I've got
something I wanna show you.

425
00:18:11,641 --> 00:18:12,892
Kay, Buckley, come here.

426
00:18:13,017 --> 00:18:14,352
I want you to see your present.

427
00:18:14,477 --> 00:18:16,187
Here, take this out
of the way, will you, Stan?

428
00:18:16,312 --> 00:18:17,563
Now, we're gonna
need lot of room.

429
00:18:17,688 --> 00:18:18,814
Here you are, old boy.

430
00:18:18,939 --> 00:18:21,692
- What is it?
- It's a blueprint!

431
00:18:21,817 --> 00:18:23,486
Here, hand me that chair.

432
00:18:23,611 --> 00:18:25,613
A blueprint for the future.

433
00:18:25,738 --> 00:18:27,657
A blueprint for happiness.

434
00:18:27,782 --> 00:18:30,034
Here now, Stan, just hold
that side down, will you?

435
00:18:30,159 --> 00:18:32,119
And you hold
the other side, Ellie.

436
00:18:32,244 --> 00:18:34,497
There now, you two kids,
take a look at that.

437
00:18:34,622 --> 00:18:35,665
What is it?

438
00:18:35,790 --> 00:18:38,292
- It's your new home.
- Home?

439
00:18:38,417 --> 00:18:40,211
- What do you mean?
- Well, I'll tell you.

440
00:18:40,336 --> 00:18:42,296
I was looking over our house
just the other day.

441
00:18:42,421 --> 00:18:44,382
And it came to me
like an inspiration.

442
00:18:44,507 --> 00:18:47,927
That whole west wing, it was
the perfect place for you kids.

443
00:18:48,052 --> 00:18:50,680
So I called up my architect
and I had him come right out.

444
00:18:50,805 --> 00:18:52,223
Here, let me show you.

445
00:18:52,348 --> 00:18:55,685
Your own study, your own
living room, dining alcove,

446
00:18:55,810 --> 00:18:57,770
kitchen and laundry,

447
00:18:57,895 --> 00:19:00,815
and over here,
baby's room, nurse's room,

448
00:19:00,940 --> 00:19:02,900
and master bedroom.

449
00:19:03,025 --> 00:19:05,027
And it's all plenty commodious.

450
00:19:05,152 --> 00:19:06,570
Ellie was fit to be tied.

451
00:19:06,696 --> 00:19:09,073
She saw that baby
slipping out of her hands.

452
00:19:09,198 --> 00:19:12,451
The living room is 26x22.
Is that big enough?

453
00:19:12,576 --> 00:19:15,913
And best of all, you'll have
two babysitters ready made.

454
00:19:16,038 --> 00:19:17,707
That's right.

455
00:19:17,832 --> 00:19:19,709
Well, kids, how about it?

456
00:19:19,834 --> 00:19:22,378
Why, it's wonderful,
isn't it, Buckley?

457
00:19:22,503 --> 00:19:24,505
Yeah, yeah. Gee, Dad,
that's swell of you.

458
00:19:24,630 --> 00:19:25,506
I'll get that tea now.

459
00:19:25,631 --> 00:19:26,590
Now you understand, of course,

460
00:19:26,716 --> 00:19:28,884
that there's nothing final
about these particular plans.

461
00:19:29,009 --> 00:19:30,594
I just thought I'd give you
a general idea

462
00:19:30,720 --> 00:19:32,012
of what it might look like.

463
00:19:32,138 --> 00:19:34,306
Now, if you'd like
to have your entrance here,

464
00:19:34,432 --> 00:19:35,641
well that can be managed.

465
00:19:35,766 --> 00:19:36,767
I'll call up the architect...

466
00:19:36,892 --> 00:19:38,227
- What's the matter, Ellie?
- It's all your fault.

467
00:19:38,352 --> 00:19:39,854
It never would â€”
would have happened

468
00:19:39,979 --> 00:19:41,856
if you'd let me ask them here.

469
00:19:41,981 --> 00:19:43,023
Ellie, I don't get it.

470
00:19:43,149 --> 00:19:44,608
You're more excited
about this baby

471
00:19:44,734 --> 00:19:45,818
than you were about any of ours.

472
00:19:45,943 --> 00:19:47,278
Well, you don't understand.

473
00:19:47,403 --> 00:19:49,113
This is the time
that Kay needs me the most.

474
00:19:49,238 --> 00:19:51,449
I was â€” I was gonna take
so much off her shoulders.

475
00:19:51,574 --> 00:19:53,451
I was gonna help her
with the shopping

476
00:19:53,576 --> 00:19:56,662
and help fix the baby clothes
and fix the nursery.

477
00:19:56,787 --> 00:19:59,790
Alright, alright, Ellie, if
it means so much, have it here.

478
00:19:59,915 --> 00:20:01,292
- I don't care.
- Oh, it's too late now.

479
00:20:01,417 --> 00:20:03,294
They're going to the Dunstans'.
We'll never see them.

480
00:20:03,419 --> 00:20:06,338
Oh, Ellie, don't be silly now.

481
00:20:06,464 --> 00:20:09,258
You heard what
Doris Dunstan said.

482
00:20:09,383 --> 00:20:10,801
This baby was the best thing
in the world

483
00:20:10,926 --> 00:20:12,636
that ever happened to Herbert.

484
00:20:12,762 --> 00:20:14,472
To Herbert!

485
00:20:14,597 --> 00:20:17,391
They're gonna take over
that baby body and soul.

486
00:20:17,516 --> 00:20:19,351
- Ellie, this is ridiculous.
- Don't talk to me.

487
00:20:19,477 --> 00:20:20,895
You're acting like â€”

488
00:20:27,151 --> 00:20:28,736
It was so sweet of you.

489
00:20:28,861 --> 00:20:30,112
So wonderful.

490
00:20:30,237 --> 00:20:32,031
And we'll never be able
to thank you enough,

491
00:20:32,156 --> 00:20:34,241
but I-it's really better
this way.

492
00:20:34,366 --> 00:20:37,161
We'd â€” We'd only have gotten
in your way.

493
00:20:37,286 --> 00:20:39,789
I'm sorry you went to all
this trouble and expense, Dad.

494
00:20:39,914 --> 00:20:41,248
We should have told you sooner.

495
00:20:41,373 --> 00:20:42,875
Have you already bought it?

496
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:45,920
Well, practically.
We made a deposit on Sunday.

497
00:20:46,045 --> 00:20:47,588
- I see.
- What's this, Kay?

498
00:20:47,713 --> 00:20:49,131
You got a house?

499
00:20:49,256 --> 00:20:51,675
I didn't realize that you
were in a position to buy.

500
00:20:51,801 --> 00:20:54,929
Well, yeah, we got
a mortgage from the bank.

501
00:20:55,054 --> 00:20:56,347
A mortgage?

502
00:20:56,472 --> 00:20:57,473
What's wrong with a mortgage?

503
00:20:57,598 --> 00:20:59,308
I had a mortgage myself
until a few years ago.

504
00:20:59,433 --> 00:21:00,643
Tell me all about
the house, Kay.

505
00:21:00,768 --> 00:21:02,520
- Where is it?
- It's in the new development.

506
00:21:02,645 --> 00:21:04,271
It's just darling,
isn't it, Buckley?

507
00:21:04,396 --> 00:21:06,273
It's just big enough for me
to take care of easily,

508
00:21:06,398 --> 00:21:07,983
and there's a nice backyard
for the baby,

509
00:21:08,108 --> 00:21:09,777
and Bob and Bliss
are gonna buy out there.

510
00:21:09,902 --> 00:21:11,987
- Is it furnished?
- Well, uh, no, it isn't.

511
00:21:12,112 --> 00:21:13,948
But we thought we could buy
some unpainted furniture.

512
00:21:14,073 --> 00:21:16,867
Oh, you can't lift a finger.
You don't have to do a thing.

513
00:21:16,992 --> 00:21:19,328
I'll do the whole business.
What's a mother for?

514
00:21:19,453 --> 00:21:20,538
I'd like to know.

515
00:21:20,663 --> 00:21:22,289
Ellie was off again.

516
00:21:26,836 --> 00:21:27,837
For the next few weeks,

517
00:21:27,962 --> 00:21:29,672
I'd stop at the new house
to pick up Ellie.

518
00:21:29,797 --> 00:21:31,924
She was working time
and overtime.

519
00:21:41,100 --> 00:21:42,476
Hi, Pops.

520
00:21:42,601 --> 00:21:44,144
Hi, kitten.

521
00:21:46,063 --> 00:21:47,815
Well, how are ya?

522
00:21:47,940 --> 00:21:50,568
Wonderful. Come on in
and see what we're doing.

523
00:21:54,572 --> 00:21:57,116
Oh, no, you don't.
You stay out in the air.

524
00:21:57,241 --> 00:21:59,326
- I'm alright now.
- What's the matter?

525
00:21:59,451 --> 00:22:00,578
Oh, it was just
the smell of the paint.

526
00:22:00,703 --> 00:22:01,829
Well, it still smells.

527
00:22:01,954 --> 00:22:03,873
Stanley, make her stay out here
while Buckley comes to get her.

528
00:22:03,998 --> 00:22:05,332
He ought to be here any minute.

529
00:22:05,457 --> 00:22:06,876
Let's sit in the shade.

530
00:22:07,001 --> 00:22:09,211
I feel so guilty.
Mom's doing so much.

531
00:22:09,336 --> 00:22:12,089
Oh, nonsense. You know that's
the breath of life for her.

532
00:22:12,214 --> 00:22:13,549
Where do we sit?

533
00:22:13,674 --> 00:22:15,009
How about over here?

534
00:22:15,134 --> 00:22:16,844
There?

535
00:22:16,969 --> 00:22:18,345
How do you like the house, Pops?

536
00:22:18,470 --> 00:22:20,681
- Oh, I think it's just right.
- Doris just loved it.

537
00:22:20,806 --> 00:22:21,807
They said they never
would have moved

538
00:22:21,932 --> 00:22:23,517
if it hadn't gotten
too small for them.

539
00:22:23,642 --> 00:22:24,935
Hmm.

540
00:22:25,060 --> 00:22:27,730
Oh, that must be little Bobby's.
I'll send it to him.

541
00:22:29,648 --> 00:22:34,570
Pops, how did you feel
when you had your first baby?

542
00:22:34,695 --> 00:22:37,281
Did it make any difference
between you and Moms?

543
00:22:37,406 --> 00:22:40,117
I-I mean how did you feel?

544
00:22:40,242 --> 00:22:41,535
Well, I felt fine.

545
00:22:41,660 --> 00:22:43,120
I mean, really?

546
00:22:43,829 --> 00:22:45,623
Well, I felt alright.

547
00:22:45,748 --> 00:22:48,125
Well, I guess my nose was
a little out of joint at first.

548
00:22:48,250 --> 00:22:50,127
I'd been high man with
your mother for over a year,

549
00:22:50,252 --> 00:22:52,296
and then suddenly you came along
and took the spotlight.

550
00:22:52,421 --> 00:22:53,672
You must have hated me.

551
00:22:53,797 --> 00:22:56,258
No, no, I don't think
it was that bad.

552
00:22:57,384 --> 00:22:58,844
I think the worst time
was the first night

553
00:22:58,969 --> 00:23:00,012
we took you home, you know.

554
00:23:01,430 --> 00:23:02,723
Yeah, I remember
we got you home,

555
00:23:02,848 --> 00:23:05,851
gave you your 6:00 feeding,
got you bedded down.

556
00:23:05,976 --> 00:23:07,770
Then we must have gone
to your room a dozen times

557
00:23:07,895 --> 00:23:09,647
the next hour
to see how you were.

558
00:23:09,772 --> 00:23:11,815
Of course, if you were quiet, we
went in to see if you were dead.

559
00:23:11,941 --> 00:23:14,443
And if you cried, we went in
to see what was wrong with you.

560
00:23:15,444 --> 00:23:17,363
I remember lying awake
that night thinking to myself,

561
00:23:17,488 --> 00:23:18,447
"Now, what have we got into?

562
00:23:18,572 --> 00:23:20,991
Here we were,
two perfectly happy people,

563
00:23:21,116 --> 00:23:22,618
free as the air.

564
00:23:22,743 --> 00:23:24,703
Now we're trapped.

565
00:23:24,828 --> 00:23:27,623
Trapped by 20 inches
of screaming humanity."

566
00:23:27,748 --> 00:23:29,458
Do all fathers feel that way?

567
00:23:29,583 --> 00:23:31,543
I only know about myself.

568
00:23:31,669 --> 00:23:34,797
I remember that morning
you â€” you woke with the dawn...

569
00:23:35,714 --> 00:23:37,716
screaming your head off.

570
00:23:37,841 --> 00:23:39,677
And your mother went in
to heat your formula,

571
00:23:39,802 --> 00:23:42,596
and I went in to see what
I could do about quieting you.

572
00:23:43,722 --> 00:23:47,059
And I stuck a finger at you,
and you grabbed it.

573
00:23:47,184 --> 00:23:49,269
Grabbed it with such a grip.

574
00:23:50,771 --> 00:23:53,649
From that moment on,
you had me hooked.

575
00:23:53,774 --> 00:23:55,693
Oh, I hope Buckley
gets over there quickly.

576
00:23:55,818 --> 00:23:57,486
You have to butter him up
a little, you know.

577
00:23:57,611 --> 00:23:59,321
Make him think he's still
part of the family.

578
00:23:59,446 --> 00:24:01,156
Thanks, Pops.

579
00:24:01,281 --> 00:24:02,658
Oh, there he is.

580
00:24:02,783 --> 00:24:04,243
Hi, honey.

581
00:24:04,368 --> 00:24:07,955
- Hi, honey.
- How are you, darling? Ahh!

582
00:24:08,080 --> 00:24:10,541
- Oh, hello, there! How are ya?
- Fine, thank you.

583
00:24:10,666 --> 00:24:13,127
Well, what new wonders
did we accomplish today?

584
00:24:13,252 --> 00:24:14,586
You're gonna see it tomorrow.
Take her along now.

585
00:24:14,712 --> 00:24:16,547
- You'll be late for the party.
- Mom, Buckley can help.

586
00:24:16,672 --> 00:24:18,382
There's nothing left to do.
Your father and I will lock up.

587
00:24:18,507 --> 00:24:20,009
- Have fun.
- Well, okay.

588
00:24:20,134 --> 00:24:22,511
- Goodbye. Goodbye, Stanley.
- Where you going?

589
00:24:22,636 --> 00:24:24,805
Stan, come here.
I want to show you.

590
00:24:25,639 --> 00:24:26,640
How do you like this green?

591
00:24:26,765 --> 00:24:27,975
Isn't it a perfectly
wonderful shade?

592
00:24:28,100 --> 00:24:29,351
- We're gonna use it in here.
- Fine.

593
00:24:29,476 --> 00:24:30,519
And in the hall and every place.

594
00:24:30,644 --> 00:24:31,729
It'll make the house
look much larger.

595
00:24:31,854 --> 00:24:33,230
And the same thing
with the curtain.

596
00:24:33,355 --> 00:24:34,857
I got the most wonderful
bargain today.

597
00:24:34,982 --> 00:24:36,775
A Millen, look at that.

598
00:24:36,900 --> 00:24:39,570
For all the windows.
And this is for the bedroom.

599
00:24:39,695 --> 00:24:40,612
Just wait till you see
the price.

600
00:24:40,738 --> 00:24:41,780
You'll be very proud of me.

601
00:24:41,905 --> 00:24:43,240
I'm staying right
within their budget.

602
00:24:43,365 --> 00:24:45,325
I'm having a marvelous time.

603
00:24:45,451 --> 00:24:47,453
There's only one thing wrong.

604
00:24:48,746 --> 00:24:50,622
I haven't done a thing
about the nursery.

605
00:24:50,748 --> 00:24:52,124
I could cry about it.

606
00:24:52,249 --> 00:24:53,333
What's the matter?

607
00:24:53,459 --> 00:24:55,878
- Herbert's doing it.
- Dunstan?

608
00:24:56,003 --> 00:24:57,713
He was so upset about
their not moving in with him.

609
00:24:57,838 --> 00:24:58,797
He said the least they could do

610
00:24:58,922 --> 00:25:00,090
would be to let him
furnish the nursery.

611
00:25:00,215 --> 00:25:02,176
He's going to give them
a crib and a bassinet

612
00:25:02,301 --> 00:25:03,677
and a screen
and a chest of drawers.

613
00:25:03,802 --> 00:25:06,847
It'll probably all be done
in 14-karat gold.

614
00:25:08,515 --> 00:25:10,225
What are we gonna give the baby?

615
00:25:10,350 --> 00:25:11,769
Stan!

616
00:25:11,894 --> 00:25:13,270
What are you so surprised about?

617
00:25:13,395 --> 00:25:14,813
Didn't you think I was gonna
give the baby a present?

618
00:25:14,938 --> 00:25:16,315
Well, as a matter of fact,
there was something

619
00:25:16,440 --> 00:25:18,525
I was looking at today that
would make a wonderful present.

620
00:25:18,650 --> 00:25:20,569
You put it right in this window,
and it keeps the air clean

621
00:25:20,694 --> 00:25:21,820
and the right temperature.

622
00:25:21,945 --> 00:25:23,572
It's very pretty
and modern-looking.

623
00:25:23,697 --> 00:25:25,657
- It's quite expensive.
- What's the name of it?

624
00:25:25,783 --> 00:25:27,910
I don't know the name of it, but
it will only extend this far.

625
00:25:28,035 --> 00:25:30,746
- Where did you see it?
- Downtown.

626
00:25:30,871 --> 00:25:33,040
You see, uh,
you regulate it from here.

627
00:25:33,165 --> 00:25:35,834
It controls the air and the
temperature at all times, see.

628
00:25:36,627 --> 00:25:38,420
No dust, no soot, no pollen.

629
00:25:38,545 --> 00:25:40,214
- Hmm.
- Wonderful. Ellie's idea.

630
00:25:40,339 --> 00:25:41,298
Wish we'd had one for Tommy.

631
00:25:41,423 --> 00:25:43,258
He probably wouldn't
have those adenoids.

632
00:25:43,383 --> 00:25:45,177
It is wonderful.
And look over here.

633
00:25:45,302 --> 00:25:46,804
Come here.
I want to show you this.

634
00:25:46,929 --> 00:25:48,013
Now, you see?

635
00:25:48,138 --> 00:25:51,433
You turn it on and leave it here
beside his crib.

636
00:25:51,558 --> 00:25:53,268
And then you can go out
and close the door.

637
00:25:53,393 --> 00:25:54,311
And if he cries

638
00:25:54,436 --> 00:25:56,605
or even if there's any change
in his breathing,

639
00:25:56,730 --> 00:25:58,190
you can hear it
from anywhere in the house.

640
00:25:58,315 --> 00:26:00,150
No. Hmm, well, they're
certainly gonna love that.

641
00:26:00,275 --> 00:26:03,112
And here's his combination
bath and dressing table.

642
00:26:03,237 --> 00:26:04,696
Right, just the right size.

643
00:26:04,822 --> 00:26:06,115
What is that?
What is that?

644
00:26:06,240 --> 00:26:08,242
Oh, that's mine. I thought he
might as well get used to it.

645
00:26:08,367 --> 00:26:09,409
He'll going there someday.

646
00:26:09,535 --> 00:26:10,786
- Oh, he will?
- Oh, yes.

647
00:26:10,911 --> 00:26:12,663
As a matter of fact,
I've already registered him

648
00:26:12,788 --> 00:26:14,248
in the class of 1973.

649
00:26:14,373 --> 00:26:16,416
Mm.
I'm a Dartmouth man myself.

650
00:26:16,542 --> 00:26:17,960
Oh, that's a good college, too.

651
00:26:18,085 --> 00:26:20,087
Now, this bath, Stan, I want you
to notice the height of it.

652
00:26:20,212 --> 00:26:21,755
A good college?

653
00:26:21,880 --> 00:26:24,258
A good college?

654
00:26:25,551 --> 00:26:31,181
We beat you in football in 1947,
1948, and 1949.

655
00:26:31,306 --> 00:26:32,641
And we shall probably â€”

656
00:26:32,766 --> 00:26:36,061
And we have defeated you
five years running in hockey.

657
00:26:36,186 --> 00:26:38,564
And our bobsled team
is probably the finest

658
00:26:38,689 --> 00:26:40,440
that has ever been developed
in the history of the world.

659
00:26:40,566 --> 00:26:42,359
Ellie's make some fresh coffee.

660
00:26:42,484 --> 00:26:43,735
A good â€”

661
00:26:43,861 --> 00:26:45,696
That's one of the funniest
remarks you've ever made.

662
00:26:45,821 --> 00:26:48,782
Now, now, wait a minute.
No, no, now listen here, Stan.

663
00:26:48,907 --> 00:26:50,993
And, you know, scholastically...

664
00:26:51,118 --> 00:26:53,871
Well, what do you think
of our little nursery?

665
00:26:53,996 --> 00:26:55,664
- Isn't it lovely?
- Fine, fine.

666
00:26:55,789 --> 00:26:58,667
The wonderful thing is, most
of it can grow up with him.

667
00:26:58,792 --> 00:27:00,169
The shelves, for instance.

668
00:27:00,294 --> 00:27:02,004
It'll hold his toys now,

669
00:27:02,129 --> 00:27:04,548
but later he can use it
for his tennis racket.

670
00:27:04,673 --> 00:27:05,841
Ellie was right.

671
00:27:05,966 --> 00:27:08,677
They had taken over the baby
lock, stock, and barrel.

672
00:27:08,802 --> 00:27:10,721
- ... and things.
- Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

673
00:27:11,805 --> 00:27:12,973
Oh, thank you, dear.

674
00:27:13,098 --> 00:27:14,516
Isn't that a beautiful
record, Pops?

675
00:27:14,641 --> 00:27:15,809
Mm-hmm.

676
00:27:15,934 --> 00:27:18,187
Mother Dunstan gave it to me.
She gave me the whole album.

677
00:27:18,312 --> 00:27:20,772
I remember that I used to
listen to classical music

678
00:27:20,898 --> 00:27:22,608
while I was waiting for Buckley.

679
00:27:22,733 --> 00:27:25,402
I think that's why
he whistles so well.

680
00:27:25,527 --> 00:27:27,112
Have you ever heard him whistle?

681
00:27:27,905 --> 00:27:29,823
No, no, I haven't.

682
00:27:29,948 --> 00:27:31,617
Well, you should
ask him sometime.

683
00:27:31,742 --> 00:27:33,744
Yes, I will.
I certainly will.

684
00:27:33,869 --> 00:27:35,287
By the way, son,
what are you going to call

685
00:27:35,412 --> 00:27:36,121
this baby of yours?

686
00:27:36,246 --> 00:27:37,497
We've had some terrible
arguments about it.

687
00:27:37,623 --> 00:27:38,498
Haven't we, Buckley?

688
00:27:38,624 --> 00:27:40,292
We've gone through
all the telephone books,

689
00:27:40,417 --> 00:27:42,085
the dictionaries,
the baby books.

690
00:27:42,211 --> 00:27:44,838
Finally, we found a couple
of names we both liked.

691
00:27:44,963 --> 00:27:47,090
Come on, sit down here.
Sit down.

692
00:27:47,216 --> 00:27:49,760
Uh, if it's a boy, we thought
we might call him Andrew.

693
00:27:49,885 --> 00:27:51,178
Andrew? Who's Andrew?

694
00:27:51,303 --> 00:27:54,723
Well, there's a Andrew Jackson
and Andrew Nordell, my doctor.

695
00:27:54,848 --> 00:27:56,892
And besides, we like
the name Andrew.

696
00:27:57,935 --> 00:27:59,561
And â€” And we both like
the name Jonathan.

697
00:27:59,686 --> 00:28:02,397
Oh, no, not Jonathan.
Better call him plain John.

698
00:28:02,522 --> 00:28:05,400
Well, we also thought
we might call him Michael.

699
00:28:05,525 --> 00:28:06,401
That's a good name.

700
00:28:06,526 --> 00:28:07,736
Oh, you can't call him Michael.

701
00:28:07,861 --> 00:28:10,739
I went to school with a Michael,
and he smelled.

702
00:28:10,864 --> 00:28:13,116
Well, now, Ellie, just because
your Michael smelled,

703
00:28:13,242 --> 00:28:16,620
you know, it doesn't mean that
all Michaels have to smell.

704
00:28:16,745 --> 00:28:18,121
You know a name that I've loved

705
00:28:18,247 --> 00:28:20,749
ever since I first read
"Little Women"?

706
00:28:20,874 --> 00:28:23,502
Lauren, Laurie.
Remember how dear he was?

707
00:28:23,627 --> 00:28:25,379
How about Timothy?
I think that has everything.

708
00:28:25,504 --> 00:28:27,047
Do you like the name
of Timothy, Kay?

709
00:28:27,172 --> 00:28:27,965
Well, I â€”

710
00:28:28,090 --> 00:28:29,591
Now, Ellie,
they've already told you

711
00:28:29,716 --> 00:28:31,677
they've been all through this.

712
00:28:31,802 --> 00:28:34,179
Why do we suggest
any more names?

713
00:28:34,304 --> 00:28:36,431
Besides, the names
they have are wonderful.

714
00:28:36,556 --> 00:28:39,601
Jonathan, Michael, Andrew,
they're all wonderful names.

715
00:28:39,726 --> 00:28:42,938
But you have to think
of two names that go together.

716
00:28:43,063 --> 00:28:47,109
Andrew Dunstan, that doesn't
sound very good, does it?

717
00:28:47,234 --> 00:28:48,860
Stanley, they haven't
made up their minds.

718
00:28:48,986 --> 00:28:49,987
They need our help.

719
00:28:50,112 --> 00:28:51,238
If I may interrupt, I think

720
00:28:51,363 --> 00:28:52,990
you're going about this
all wrong.

721
00:28:53,115 --> 00:28:55,200
My idea would be
to use a family name.

722
00:28:55,325 --> 00:28:56,451
Well, that's right.

723
00:28:56,576 --> 00:28:59,579
The first grandson is always
supposed to have the name

724
00:28:59,705 --> 00:29:01,290
of the paternal grandfather,
isn't it?

725
00:29:01,415 --> 00:29:03,959
No, no, no. Now, Doris,
that's not what I meant.

726
00:29:04,084 --> 00:29:06,295
I was thinking of
my great-grandfather Malcolm

727
00:29:06,420 --> 00:29:08,255
or, we", say Uncle Wilfred.

728
00:29:08,380 --> 00:29:10,132
Well, if we're talking
about family names,

729
00:29:10,257 --> 00:29:11,466
what about Stanley?

730
00:29:11,591 --> 00:29:14,219
Stanley Dunstan, that ought
to satisfy everybody.

731
00:29:14,344 --> 00:29:16,179
Well, we did think about that.

732
00:29:16,305 --> 00:29:17,848
No, no, no, no.

733
00:29:17,973 --> 00:29:21,184
No, one Stanley
in the family is enough.

734
00:29:21,310 --> 00:29:22,853
You're right.
